"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62332","Home Office","false","2014-07-01","<p>Her Majesty's Passport Office does not hold the information in the form requested. The <br>cost of providing it from individual applicant data held would be <br>disproportionate.</p><p> </p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2014-07-01T14:01:31.8276183Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62332/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62332/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62332/answer","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62332/answer/previousversion/4325","Biography information for James Brokenshire","1","Home Office","Home Office","2014-06-17","Passports: Ashfield","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many passport applications from residents of Ashfield constituency received more than three weeks ago HM Passport Office are processing.","false","Biography information for Gloria De Piero","Ashfield","Gloria De Piero","201023"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62333","Home Office","false","2014-07-01","<p> </p><p>Her Majesty's Passport Office does not hold the information in the form requested. The <br>cost of providing it from individual applicant data held would be <br>disproportionate.</p><p> </p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2014-07-01T13:38:08.7916956Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62333/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62333/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62333/answer","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62333/answer/previousversion/4327","Biography information for James Brokenshire","1","Home Office","Home Office","2014-06-17","Passports: Ashfield","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many passport applications from residents of Ashfield constituency received in the last three months were not processed by HM Passport Office in three weeks.","false","Biography information for Gloria De Piero","Ashfield","Gloria De Piero","201024"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62334","Home Office","false","2014-06-24","<p> </p><p>To date 50 Syrians have arrived in the UK under the Syrian Vulnerable Persons Relocation scheme. <br><br>The scheme is based on need, rather than designed to meet set arrival projections. However, we will continue to bring groups here on a regular basis, and envisage that several hundred people will be helped over the next three years.</p><p> </p>","Staffordshire Moorlands","Karen Bradley",,"2014-06-24T13:47:01.4218393Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62334/answer","Biography information for Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62334/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62334/answer","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62334/answer/previousversion/4333","Biography information for James Brokenshire","1","Home Office","Home Office","2014-06-17","Asylum: Syria","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many people have been resettled in the UK under the Syrian Vulnerable Persons Relocation scheme since its launch; and how many people are expected to arrive in the UK under that scheme by December 2014.","false","Biography information for Dr Julian Huppert","Cambridge","Dr Julian Huppert","200675"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62335","Home Office","false","2014-07-02","<p> </p><p>I refer the Hon. Member to the reply given on 19 June 2014, Official Report, columns 666-667W. <br>Following two linked international investigations into the boylover.net <br>website, information was provided to the Child Exploitation and Online <br>Protection Centre (CEOP) by US authorities and Europol that related to UK-based <br>registered users. CEOP was, at that time, an affiliate of the Serious Organised <br>Crime Agency. We do not maintain a record of the number of UK-registered users <br>of the website identified by United States or Dutch authorities, nor of what <br>proportion of those users were passed to CEOP. However, as a consequence of the <br>information provided and through CEOP's own investigations, 240 intelligence <br>packages were prepared and subsequently disseminated to police forces across <br>the UK. Further information regarding charges, convictions and open <br>investigations is handled at a local level by the relevant police force and <br>is not recorded nationally.</p><p> </p>","Lewes","Norman Baker",,"2014-07-02T10:56:03.2339205Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62335/answer","Biography information for Norman Baker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62335/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62335/answer","Lewes","Norman Baker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62335/answer/previousversion/4358","Biography information for Norman Baker","1","Home Office","Home Office","2014-06-17","Offences against Children: Internet","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what information her Department holds on how many UK-based registered users of the paedophile file sharing network website boylover.net have been identified by international authorities in (a) the US and (b) Holland; what proportion of those was passed to UK authorities for investigation; what steps her Department is taking to trace  those registered users; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Tom Watson","West Bromwich East","Mr Tom Watson","201056"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62336","Home Office","false","2014-06-23","<p> </p><p>The Government's response to the report from the Joint Committee on the draft <br>Modern Slavery Bill was published on 10 June 2014. Copies of the report are <br>available in the House Library. <br><br>The response was also published on the Gov.UK website: <br>https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/draft-modern-slavery-bill--2</p><p> </p>","Staffordshire Moorlands","Karen Bradley",,"2014-06-23T15:32:40.6156805Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62336/answer","Biography information for Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62336/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62336/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2014-06-17","Modern Slavery Bill","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, whether she expects to respond to the recommendations of the Report by the Joint Committee on the Draft Modern Slavery Bill by the time of Second Reading of that Bill.","false","Biography information for David Hanson","Delyn","Mr David Hanson","201114"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62337","Home Office","false","2014-06-26","<p> </p><p> </p><p>Domestic violence is a dreadful form of abuse and is not acceptable within our <br>society. The Coalition Government's approach to tackling domestic violence and <br>abuse is set out in its Violence against Women and Girls Action Plan, updated in March <br>2014.<br><br>In 2013, the Home Secretary commissioned Her Majesty's Inspectorate of <br>Constabulary to undertake a comprehensive review on how the police deal with<br>domestic violence and abuse. HMIC's report exposed significant failings. In response<br>to the Review, the Home Secretary has established a National Oversight Group, which <br>she is chairing, and on which I sit, to ensure HMIC's recommendations are acted upon.<br>The Group met for the first time on 10 June. The Home Secretary has also written to chief constables making it clear that every police force must have an action plan in place by September 2014, to improve their response to domestic violence and abuse.<br><br>The Government is committed to ensuring that the police and other agencies have <br>the tools necessary to tackle domestic violence, to bring offenders to justice <br>and to ensure victims have the support they need to rebuild their lives. On 8 <br>March 2014, the Government announced the national roll-out of Domestic Violence <br>Protection Orders following the successful conclusion of a one-year <br>pilot in three police force areas including Wiltshire, as well as the Domestic <br>Violence Disclosure Scheme following the successful conclusion in <br>September 2013 of a one-year pilot in four police force areas – once again <br>including Wiltshire.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Lewes","Norman Baker",,"2014-06-26T15:22:10.2229767Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62337/answer","Biography information for Norman Baker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62337/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62337/answer","Lewes","Norman Baker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62337/answer/previousversion/4350","Biography information for Norman Baker","1","Home Office","Home Office","2014-06-17","Domestic Abuse","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what recent steps her Department is taking to help end domestic abuse and violence against women.","false","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson","201115"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62338","Home Office","false","2014-06-26","<p> </p><p>Last September, the Home Secretary commissioned Her Majesty's Inspectorate of <br>Constabulary to conduct a review of the response to domestic abuse <br>across all police forces. HMIC published its findings in March 2014, <br>emphasising that the key priority is a culture change in the police so that <br>domestic violence and abuse is treated as the crime that it is and that the <br>police use the full range of tools already available to them. <br><br>In response to the Review, the Home Secretary has established a new national <br>oversight group, which she is chairing, and on which I sit, to oversee delivery <br>against each of HMIC's recommendations. Their first meeting was held <br>on 10 June. The Home Secretary has also written to chief constables making it clear<br>that every police force must have an action plan in place by September 2014. <br><br>There are a number of offences that make domestic abuse illegal, including <br>actual bodily harm, grievous bodily harm and assault. Assault can extend to <br>non-physical harm. This Government has introduced stalking and harassment <br>legislation which can apply to coercive control and psychological abuse. <br>However, the Government will continue to consider what measures will drive <br>culture change in the police in response to the findings of the HMIC review.</p><p> </p>","Lewes","Norman Baker","201085","2014-06-26T16:08:31.848382Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62338/answer","Biography information for Norman Baker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62338/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62338/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2014-06-17","Domestic Abuse","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what plans her Department has to bring forward proposals to criminalise coercive control and psychological abuse for the purpose of protection of victims of domestic violence.","false","Biography information for Mr Brooks Newmark","Braintree","Mr Brooks Newmark","201084"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62339","Home Office","false","2014-09-01","<p> </p><p>External Communication is defined within the Regulation of Investigatory Powers Act (RIPA) 2000 and the statutory Interception of Communications Code of Practice which was approved by Parliament and came into force on 1 July 2002. The Government has no present plans to amend the definition of external communication.<br><br>Under RIPA, interception warrants are issued by the Secretary of State.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2014-09-01T13:25:12.8856993Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62339/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62339/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62339/answer","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62339/answer/previousversion/4322","Biography information for James Brokenshire","1","Home Office","Home Office","2014-06-17","Electronic Surveillance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, whether she authorised the UK's classification of (a) Google, (b) Facebook, (c) webmail services and (d) other companies that operate in the UK as external communications.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","201104"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62340","Home Office","false","2014-08-04","<p>External Communication is defined within the Regulation of Investigatory Powers Act (RIPA) 2000 and the statutory Interception of Communications Code of Practice which was approved by Parliament and came into force on 1 July 2002. The Government has no present plans to amend the definition of external communication.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2014-08-04T15:35:21.0309108Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62340/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62340/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62340/answer","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62340/answer/previousversion/4323","Biography information for James Brokenshire","1","Home Office","Home Office","2014-06-17","Electronic Surveillance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, whether the Government plans to bring forward legislative proposals to change (a) the classification of external communications for the purposes of interception and (b) other aspects of UK surveillance law.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","201105"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62341","Home Office","false","2014-06-26","<p> </p><p>Last September, the Home Secretary commissioned Her Majesty's Inspectorate of <br>Constabulary to conduct a review of the response to domestic abuse <br>across all police forces. HMIC published its findings in March 2014, <br>emphasising that the key priority is a culture change in the police so that <br>domestic violence and abuse is treated as the crime that it is and that the <br>police use the full range of tools already available to them. <br><br>In response to the Review, the Home Secretary has established a new national <br>oversight group, which she is chairing, and on which I sit, to oversee delivery <br>against each of HMIC's recommendations. Their first meeting was held <br>on 10 June. The Home Secretary has also written to chief constables making it clear<br>that every police force must have an action plan in place by September 2014. <br><br>There are a number of offences that make domestic abuse illegal, including <br>actual bodily harm, grievous bodily harm and assault. Assault can extend to <br>non-physical harm. This Government has introduced stalking and harassment <br>legislation which can apply to coercive control and psychological abuse. <br>However, the Government will continue to consider what measures will drive <br>culture change in the police in response to the findings of the HMIC review.</p><p> </p>","Lewes","Norman Baker","201084","2014-06-26T16:08:31.7808637Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62341/answer","Biography information for Norman Baker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62341/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62341/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2014-06-17","Domestic Abuse","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what plans her Department has in response to the HM Inspector of Constabulary Inquiry into police response to domestic violence in creating a culture change towards domestic violence.","false","Biography information for Mr Brooks Newmark","Braintree","Mr Brooks Newmark","201085"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62342","Home Office","false","2014-06-23","<p> </p><p> </p><p>No Minister or Special Adviser at the Home Office authorised the release of information about the forthcoming proscription to The Sun newspaper.</p><p> </p><p>I have written in response to the point of order reiterating that we take Parliamentary business very seriously and always seek to follow Mr Speaker's preference that the House is informed first of the Home Secretary's intention to proscribe terrorist groups. This was our intent on this occasion.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2014-06-23T11:28:58.7966877Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62342/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62342/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62342/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2014-06-17","Disclosure of Information","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, who within her Department authorised the passing of information about forthcoming proscription orders to The Sun newspaper; and whether that authorisation was agreed by a Minister or special adviser in her Department.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","201134"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62343","Home Office","false","2014-06-24","<p> </p><p>The Home Office does not comment on individual cases.</p><p> </p>","Staffordshire Moorlands","Karen Bradley",,"2014-06-24T13:57:42.5846021Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62343/answer","Biography information for Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62343/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62343/answer","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62343/answer/previousversion/4317","Biography information for James Brokenshire","1","Home Office","Home Office","2014-06-17","Didier Pierre Paulet","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, whether the deportation order served on Didier Pierre Paulet on 19 November 2007 pursuant to a recommendation by a Crown Court Judge for deportation has been implemented; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Sir Christopher Chope","Christchurch","Mr Christopher Chope","201127"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62344","Northern Ireland Office","false","2014-06-23","<p> </p><p>No invoices have been submitted for payment in respect of legal work in connection with the Saville Inquiry. An invoice was submitted in March 2013 for hosting of the Inquiry website.</p><p> </p>","Chipping Barnet","Mrs Theresa Villiers",,"2014-06-23T14:52:42.6473349Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62344/answer","Biography information for Theresa Villiers","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62344/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62344/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2014-06-17","Bloody Sunday Tribunal of Inquiry","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, whether invoices for legal or other work carried out in connection with the Savile Inquiry have been submitted for payment since January 2013.","false","Biography information for Mr Gregory Campbell","East Londonderry","Mr Gregory Campbell","200995"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62345","Home Office","false","2014-06-26","<p> </p><p>It is a statutory requirement that social housing meets the Decent Homes <br>Standard as defined in the Housing Act 2004.<br><br>All COMPASS contracts incorporate the requirements of the Decent Home Standards <br>for social housing as part of the contractual performance management <br>arrangements and are robustly monitored through three key performance <br>indicators which relate specifically to property standards. <br><br>Providers are required to inspect all properties on a monthly basis or at the <br>point when a service user first occupies the property. In addition, the Home <br>Office has a team of 17 contract compliance officers who also closely monitor <br>property standards as part of their contract compliance and assurance role.<br><br>Any failure of the critical service levels may result in financial penalties.</p><p> </p>","Staffordshire Moorlands","Karen Bradley",,"2014-06-26T15:59:34.1918034Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62345/answer","Biography information for Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62345/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62345/answer","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62345/answer/previousversion/4334","Biography information for James Brokenshire","1","Home Office","Home Office","2014-06-17","Compass Contracts","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what steps her Department takes to ensure that accommodation provided by the COMPASS contracts meets the Decent Homes Standards.","false","Biography information for Dr Julian Huppert","Cambridge","Dr Julian Huppert","201006"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62346","Home Office","false","2014-06-26","<p> </p><p>The COMPASS contracts lay down requirements for the management of enquiries and <br>complaints received in respect of accommodation services provided to asylum <br>seekers.<br><br>COMPASS providers have a complaints service in place through which the asylum <br>seeker, their representative, the voluntary sector or local authorities can <br>raise concerns or issues direct. Providers also provide asylum seekers with a <br>detailed briefing on how they can raise a complaint as part of the move in <br>process. Asylum seekers can raise a complaint in a confidential way, and with <br>the assistance of an interpreter when required.<br><br>The complaints process is subject to performance management under the Key <br>Performance Indicators regime. Providers are required to report their <br>performance in terms of dealing with complaints on a monthly basis. In <br>addition, the Home Office has a team of 17 contract compliance officers who <br>also closely monitor complaints made to providers or made direct to the Home <br>Office as part of their contract compliance and assurance role.<br><br>Any failure of the critical service levels may result in financial penalties.</p><p> </p>","Staffordshire Moorlands","Karen Bradley",,"2014-06-26T16:00:45.4579632Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62346/answer","Biography information for Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62346/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62346/answer","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62346/answer/previousversion/4335","Biography information for James Brokenshire","1","Home Office","Home Office","2014-06-17","Compass Contracts","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what steps her Department takes to ensure that asylum seekers in COMPASS accommodation are able to register complaints quickly and easily.","false","Biography information for Dr Julian Huppert","Cambridge","Dr Julian Huppert","201007"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62347","Home Office","false","2014-06-24","<p> </p><p>It is for Chief Constables and Police and Crime Commissioners to make decisions about whether and when to adopt the scheme.</p><p> </p>","Ashford","Damian Green",,"2014-06-24T14:05:11.9993447Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62347/answer","Biography information for Damian Green","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62347/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62347/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2014-06-17","Stop and Search","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, whether police and crime commissioners will be able to decide on the applicability of the adoption of her Department's new guidelines on the use of stop and search by police to the area they represent.","false","Biography information for Mr Douglas Carswell","Clacton","Mr Douglas Carswell","200663"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62348","Home Office","false","2014-06-24","<p> </p><p>Tackling all forms of hate crime, including that motivated by hatred of a person's sexual orientation or transgender identity is an issue the coalition Government takes very seriously. <br><br>On 1 May 2014 we published 'Challenge it, Report it, Stop it - Delivering the Government's Hate Crime Action Plan'. This progress report provides an overview of our achievements since the action plan was first published in March 2012 and sets out our key priorities for the remainder of this Parliament. A specific action in the plan includes tackling homophobia and transphobia in sports.<br><br>We are meeting the coalition commitment to improve the recording of hate crimes motivated by sexual orientation and transgender identity and are working with the police and other partners to encourage more victims to come forward. We have supported voluntary sector organisations to develop third party reporting services for LGBT victims.</p><p> </p>","Lewes","Norman Baker",,"2014-06-24T14:21:30.8281574Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62348/answer","Biography information for Norman Baker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62348/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62348/answer","Lewes","Norman Baker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62348/answer/previousversion/4342","Biography information for Norman Baker","1","Home Office","Home Office","2014-06-17","Hate Crime: LGBT People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what steps she is taking to reduce homophobic and transphobic hate crimes against LGBT people.","false","Biography information for Dan Jarvis","Barnsley Central","Dan Jarvis","201017"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62349","Home Office","false","2014-07-02","<p> </p><p>It is not possible to provide detail of how long those held in prison <br>establishments have been detained without the examination of individual records <br>at disproportionate cost.</p><p> </p>","Staffordshire Moorlands","Karen Bradley",,"2014-07-02T14:18:27.5326324Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62349/answer","Biography information for Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62349/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62349/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2014-06-17","Verne Prison","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, pursuant to the Answer to the hon. Member for Brent Central of 16 June 2014, Official Report, column 445W, on HMP Verne, in which prison establishment for how long each person detained has been held.","false","Biography information for David Hanson","Delyn","Mr David Hanson","200665"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62350","Home Office","false","2014-06-24","<p> </p><p>Essex Police have acknowledged receipt of the Home Secretary's letter sent to Chief Constables on 30th April and have advised that they will submit a formal response in due course.</p><p> </p>","Ashford","Damian Green",,"2014-06-24T13:54:29.0714833Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62350/answer","Biography information for Damian Green","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62350/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62350/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2014-06-17","Stop and Search: Essex","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what representations she received from the Essex Police and Crime Commissioner on changes to guidelines for police stop and search.","false","Biography information for Mr Douglas Carswell","Clacton","Mr Douglas Carswell","200664"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62351","Home Office","false","2014-09-09","<p /> <p>In non-European Arrest Warrant cases, the following EU Member States have an absolute bar on extraditing their own nationals: <br><br>• Austria<br>• Belgium<br>• Czech Republic<br>• France<br>• Germany<br>• Greece<br>• Latvia<br>• Luxembourg<br>• Slovakia<br>• Slovenia<br>• Spain<br><br>In addition, Finland and Sweden have an absolute bar to extraditing their own nationals to countries other than Norway &amp; Iceland.</p><p />","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2014-09-09T15:33:31.8989202Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62351/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62351/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62351/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2014-06-17","Extradition: EU Countries","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, with reference to the Answer of 14 May 2014, Official Report, column 620W, on arrest warrants, in addition to Slovakia, Latvia, Belgium and the Czech Republic, which other EU member states retain an absolute bar on extraditing nationals in non-European Arrest Warrant extradition cases.","false","Biography information for Dominic Raab","Esher and Walton","Mr Dominic Raab","201018"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62352","House of Commons Commission","false","2014-06-23","<p>The selection panel that will consider the appointment of the next Clerk of the House was chosen by Mr Speaker and its composition was considered by the House of Commons Commission at its meeting on 16 June. The criteria for selection of panel members included party balance, gender balance and the need for external independent input.</p>","Caithness, Sutherland and Easter Ross","John Thurso",,"2014-06-23T15:25:39.2951569Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62352/answer","Biography information for Viscount Thurso","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62352/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62352/answer",,,,,"18","House of Commons Commission","House of Commons Commission","2014-06-17","Clerk of the House","1","House of Commons","To ask the hon. Member for Caithness, Sutherland and Easter Ross representing the House of Commons Commission, what the criteria were for the choice of members of the panel of selection to consider the appointment of the next Clerk of the House and Chief Executive; and who selected those members.","false","Biography information for Sir Simon Burns","Chelmsford","Mr Simon Burns","201113"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62353","House of Commons Commission","false","2014-06-20","<p>The full cost of the Independent Options Appraisal is expected to be £2,423K, including VAT. The cost incurred to 18 June 2014 was £2,213K, including VAT and a sum accrued but not yet invoiced. The cost is shared 60:40 between the House of Commons and the House of Lords.</p>","Caithness, Sutherland and Easter Ross","John Thurso",,"2014-06-20T11:39:42.7069836Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62353/answer","Biography information for Viscount Thurso","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62353/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62353/answer",,,,,"18","House of Commons Commission","House of Commons Commission","2014-06-17","Palace of Westminster","1","House of Commons","To ask the hon. Member for Caithness, Sutherland and Easter Ross representing the House of Commons Commission, what the cost to date has been of the contract for the Independent Assessment of Options to Take Forward a Restoration and Renewal Programme for the Palace of Westminster awarded to Deloitte Real Estate and AECOM together with HOK in December 2013.","false","Biography information for Sir Mark Hendrick","Preston","Mark Hendrick","201103"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62354","House of Commons Commission","false","2014-06-20","<p>The House of Commons has two Audit Committees with the same membership, one for each of its Estimates: the Administration Estimate Audit Committee (AEAC) and the Members Estimate Audit Committee (MEAC). The House of Commons Administration Estimate covers the staff of the House and its running costs (the “House of Commons Service”). The Members Estimate covers certain expenditure relating to Members such as Members pensions and “Short money”.</p><p>Information about the Committees' activities is recorded on the basis of financial year, rather than Parliamentary sessions. Both Committees met six times during the financial year 2013–14. Committee members' attendance at these meetings is set out, and was the same for both Committees.</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Member </strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Total number of meetings attended </strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Dame Janet Gaymer DBE (Chair)</p></td><td><p>3/3</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Alex Jablonowski (Chair)</p></td><td><p>3/3</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Stephen Brooker</p></td><td><p>6/6</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Angela Eagle MP</p></td><td><p>0/6</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Rt Hon Sir Alan Haselhurst MP</p></td><td><p>6/6</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>John Thurso MP</p></td><td><p>5/6</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Barbara Scott</p></td><td><p>5/6</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>Information on previous financial years is in the Committees' annual reports which are at:</p><p><a href="http://www.parliament.uk/business/committees/committees-a-z/other-committees/administration-estimate-audit/publications/" target="_blank">http://www.parliament.uk/business/committees/committees-a-z/other-committees/administration-estimate-audit/publications/</a></p><p><a href="http://www.parliament.uk/business/committees/committees-a-z/other-committees/members-estimate-audit/publications/" target="_blank">http://www.parliament.uk/business/committees/committees-a-z/other-committees/members-estimate-audit/publications/</a></p><p>Individual members' attendance has been recorded in the annual reports only since financial year 2011–12. For earlier years this can be derived from the minutes of the meetings, which are also available on the Parliament Website.</p>","Caithness, Sutherland and Easter Ross","John Thurso",,"2014-06-20T09:12:08.5414023Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62354/answer","Biography information for Viscount Thurso","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62354/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62354/answer",,,,,"18","House of Commons Commission","House of Commons Commission","2014-06-17","Committees","1","House of Commons","To ask the hon. Member for Caithness, Sutherland and Easter Ross representing the House of Commons Commission, how many meetings of the Audit Committees has been held in each of the previous sessions of the current Parliament; and how many meetings each member has attended.","false","Biography information for Sir Christopher Chope","Christchurch","Mr Christopher Chope","201083"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62355","Department for International Development","false","2014-06-23","<p>We have already been clear that we agree with the importance of instruments and incentives for investments in low-carbon solutions in infrastructure and industry, and welcome consideration of these in the Open Working Group discussions on the SDGs.</p><p> </p><p>The final targets in the post-2015 development framework will however be subject to international negotiations in the United Nations, in which the UK will play an active role.</p><p> </p>","Putney","Justine Greening",,"2014-06-23T15:47:34.2336389Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62355/answer","Biography information for Justine Greening","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62355/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62355/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2014-06-17","Developing Countries: Carbon Emissions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, if she will make it her policy to support the adoption of a target to introduce instruments and incentives for investments in low-carbon solutions in infrastructure, industry and other sectors in Open Working Group negotiations on the Sustainable Development Goals.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Murphy","East Renfrewshire","Mr Jim Murphy","201117"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62356","Department for International Development","false","2014-06-23","<p>The UK supports integrating climate change adaptation and mitigation strategies into development plans and poverty reduction strategies. This language is included in the most recent draft goals and targets list released by the co-chairs of the Open Working Group (OWG) on 2 June.</p><p> </p><p>The final targets in the post-2015 development framework will be subject to international negotiations in the United Nations, in which the UK will play an active role.</p><p> </p>","Putney","Justine Greening",,"2014-06-23T15:48:50.3513741Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62356/answer","Biography information for Justine Greening","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62356/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62356/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2014-06-17","Developing Countries: Carbon Emissions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, if she will make it her policy to support the adoption of a target to integrate climate adaptation and emissions reductions into development plans and poverty reduction strategies in Open Working Group negotiations on the Sustainable Development Goals.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Murphy","East Renfrewshire","Mr Jim Murphy","201118"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62357","Department for International Development","false","2014-06-24","<p> </p><p>The Ministry of Justice (MoJ) publishes a quarterly statistics bulletin concerning FOI responses from all government departments including DFID. The bulletin includes tables showing how many requests were granted in full, or resulted in some information being withheld or all information withheld. The MoJ statistics bulletin can be found at:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/government-foi-statistics" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/government-foi-statistics</a></p><p> </p>","Putney","Justine Greening",,"2014-06-24T16:22:12.9447745Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62357/answer","Biography information for Justine Greening","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62357/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62357/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2014-06-17","Freedom of Information","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, to how many Freedom of Information requests on aid projects her Department has declined to provide information in each of the last 12 months.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","200669"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62358","Department for International Development","false","2014-06-23","<p>Following the brutal murder of Farzana Parveen in Lahore on 27 May, I raised this issue at various levels in the Government of Pakistan. The Foreign Secretary and senior HMG officials in Pakistan have also publically and privately condemned the appalling crime of ‘honour killings' and called for immediate action to bring the culprits of the 27 May attack to justice.</p><p> </p><p>HMG regularly engages with the government and civil society in Pakistan on women's rights and violence against women, including so-called 'honour killings'. Across DFID's programmes in Pakistan we are helping women and girls to live healthy and secure lives.</p><p> </p>","Putney","Justine Greening","200670 ; 200672","2014-06-23T15:36:05.0636428Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62358/answer","Biography information for Justine Greening","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62358/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62358/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2014-06-17","South Asia","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what recent discussions she has had with non-governmental organisations in Pakistan and neighbouring countries about honour killings.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Murphy","East Renfrewshire","Mr Jim Murphy","200671"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62359","Department for International Development","false","2014-06-23","<p>Following the brutal murder of Farzana Parveen in Lahore on 27 May, I raised this issue at various levels in the Government of Pakistan. The Foreign Secretary and senior HMG officials in Pakistan have also publically and privately condemned the appalling crime of ‘honour killings' and called for immediate action to bring the culprits of the 27 May attack to justice.</p><p> </p><p>HMG regularly engages with the government and civil society in Pakistan on women's rights and violence against women, including so-called 'honour killings'. Across DFID's programmes in Pakistan we are helping women and girls to live healthy and secure lives.</p><p> </p>","Putney","Justine Greening","200671 ; 200672","2014-06-23T15:36:04.9673752Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62359/answer","Biography information for Justine Greening","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62359/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62359/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2014-06-17","South Asia","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what recent discussions she has had with regional organisations in Pakistan and neighbouring countries about honour killings.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Murphy","East Renfrewshire","Mr Jim Murphy","200670"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62360","Department for International Development","false","2014-06-23","<p>Following the brutal murder of Farzana Parveen in Lahore on 27 May, I raised this issue at various levels in the Government of Pakistan. The Foreign Secretary and senior HMG officials in Pakistan have also publically and privately condemned the appalling crime of ‘honour killings' and called for immediate action to bring the culprits of the 27 May attack to justice.</p><p> </p><p>HMG regularly engages with the government and civil society in Pakistan on women's rights and violence against women, including so-called 'honour killings'. Across DFID's programmes in Pakistan we are helping women and girls to live healthy and secure lives.</p><p> </p>","Putney","Justine Greening","200670 ; 200671","2014-06-23T15:36:05.1417755Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62360/answer","Biography information for Justine Greening","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62360/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62360/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2014-06-17","South Asia","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what recent discussions she has had with her counterparts in Pakistan and neighbouring countries about honour killings.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Murphy","East Renfrewshire","Mr Jim Murphy","200672"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62361","Ministry of Justice","false","2014-06-24","<p /> <p /> <p>The CMR Unit aims to conduct all investigations in a proportionate and efficient manner. This means determining as quickly as possible whether a CMC under investigation is in breach of the conditions of its authorisation. If following an investigation it is clear that those conditions have been breached and there is a public protection issue, any proposed enforcement action will be expedited.</p><p> </p><p>(1) 6 June 2013 was the earliest date from when the Claims Management Regulation (CMR) Unit began an investigation under regulation 35, which remains unresolved but no enforcement proceedings have yet commenced.</p><p> </p><p>(2) Information is available for the period, 12 months to 18 June 2014. The CMR Unit conducted 46 investigations under regulation 35, which took an average of 5 months, 21 days before enforcement proceedings were taken, and an average of 2 months, 8 days before being closed without the requirement for enforcement proceedings.</p><p> </p><p>(3) As at 18 June 2014, the CMR Unit was investigating 24 CMCs under regulation 35.</p>","North West Cambridgeshire","Mr Shailesh Vara","200998 ; 200999","2014-06-24T11:32:32.1436096Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62361/answer","Biography information for Mr Shailesh Vara","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62361/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62361/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2014-06-17","Claims Management Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many investigations are being carried out by the Claims Management Regulation Unit under regulation 35 of the Compensation (Claims Management Services) Regulations 2006.","false","Biography information for Mr David Nuttall","Bury North","Mr David Nuttall","201004"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62362","HM Treasury","false","2014-06-23","<p>HM Revenue &amp; Customs (HMRC) is not a prosecuting authority. Where cases do proceed to the criminal courts the prosecution is carried out by the relevant independent prosecuting authority. This is the Crown Prosecution Service (CPS) in England and Wales, the Crown Office and Procurator Fiscal Service (COPFS) in Scotland, and the Public Prosecution Service for Northern Ireland (PPSNI).</p><p> </p><p>Please note that figures for tax evasion exclude those cases prosecuted for money laundering, other prohibitions and restrictions and other non-fiscal offences.</p><p> </p><p>We can provide the following information in respect of totals of tax evasion prosecutions</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Year</p></td><td><p>Total number of persons prosecuted for tax evasion</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2010-11</p></td><td><p>372</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011-12</p></td><td><p>501</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012-13</p></td><td><p>739</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013-14</p></td><td><p>880</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p><p>HMRC is not able to supply a time series of full year prosecution decisions and convictions resulting from their criminal investigations for years up to 2009–10. Complete, comparable data is only available from 2010–11 onwards.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2014-06-23T15:01:30.3847398Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62362/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62362/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62362/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2014-06-17","Tax Evasion","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many prosecutions have been brought for tax offences in each year since 2008-09.","false","Biography information for Dominic Raab","Esher and Walton","Mr Dominic Raab","201005"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62363","Ministry of Justice","false","2014-06-24","<p /> <p /> <p>The CMR Unit aims to conduct all investigations in a proportionate and efficient manner. This means determining as quickly as possible whether a CMC under investigation is in breach of the conditions of its authorisation. If following an investigation it is clear that those conditions have been breached and there is a public protection issue, any proposed enforcement action will be expedited.</p><p> </p><p>(1) 6 June 2013 was the earliest date from when the Claims Management Regulation (CMR) Unit began an investigation under regulation 35, which remains unresolved but no enforcement proceedings have yet commenced.</p><p> </p><p>(2) Information is available for the period, 12 months to 18 June 2014. The CMR Unit conducted 46 investigations under regulation 35, which took an average of 5 months, 21 days before enforcement proceedings were taken, and an average of 2 months, 8 days before being closed without the requirement for enforcement proceedings.</p><p> </p><p>(3) As at 18 June 2014, the CMR Unit was investigating 24 CMCs under regulation 35.</p>","North West Cambridgeshire","Mr Shailesh Vara","200999 ; 201004","2014-06-24T11:32:31.8316643Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62363/answer","Biography information for Mr Shailesh Vara","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62363/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62363/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2014-06-17","Claims Management Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, on what earliest date a still unresolved investigation by the Claims Management Regulation Unit under regulation 35 of the Compensation (Claims Management Services) Regulations 2006 was begun; and on what earliest date such an investigation was begun but no proceedings have yet commenced.","false","Biography information for Mr David Nuttall","Bury North","Mr David Nuttall","200998"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62364","Ministry of Justice","false","2014-06-24","<p /> <p /> <p>The CMR Unit aims to conduct all investigations in a proportionate and efficient manner. This means determining as quickly as possible whether a CMC under investigation is in breach of the conditions of its authorisation. If following an investigation it is clear that those conditions have been breached and there is a public protection issue, any proposed enforcement action will be expedited.</p><p> </p><p>(1) 6 June 2013 was the earliest date from when the Claims Management Regulation (CMR) Unit began an investigation under regulation 35, which remains unresolved but no enforcement proceedings have yet commenced.</p><p> </p><p>(2) Information is available for the period, 12 months to 18 June 2014. The CMR Unit conducted 46 investigations under regulation 35, which took an average of 5 months, 21 days before enforcement proceedings were taken, and an average of 2 months, 8 days before being closed without the requirement for enforcement proceedings.</p><p> </p><p>(3) As at 18 June 2014, the CMR Unit was investigating 24 CMCs under regulation 35.</p>","North West Cambridgeshire","Mr Shailesh Vara","200998 ; 201004","2014-06-24T11:32:31.9431922Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62364/answer","Biography information for Mr Shailesh Vara","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62364/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62364/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2014-06-17","Claims Management Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what average period of time is taken between the date of the opening of an investigation under regulation 35 of the Compensation (Claims Management Services) Regulations 2006 and the date on which (a) proceedings are commenced and (b) the case is closed without proceedings being brought.","false","Biography information for Mr David Nuttall","Bury North","Mr David Nuttall","200999"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62365","Department for Culture Media and Sport","false","2014-06-24","<p>No such assessment has been made, but we are aware that after ICO issued a large monetary penalty in November 2012 for spam text messages, the monitoring service Cloudmark reported a 10% drop in unsolicited spam SMS text messages. We remain keen to ensure robust enforcement of the regulations, so that companies breaking the rules are caught and penalised.</p><p>OurNuisance Calls Action Plan that was published on 30th March 2014, details the range of legislative and non-legislative measures being taken forward to tackle nuisance calls and texts and the plan can be viewed at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/news/nuisance-calls-action-plan-unveiled" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/news/nuisance-calls-action-plan-unveiled</a></p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2014-06-24T09:56:09.4032707Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62365/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62365/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62365/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2014-06-17","Direct Selling","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what assessment he has made of the effect of fines imposed by the Information Commissioner's Office on reducing nuisance calls and texts.","false","Biography information for Jim Sheridan","Paisley and Renfrewshire North","Jim Sheridan","200984"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62366","Ministry of Justice","false","2014-06-25","<p /> <p /> <p>Information on the average total salary cost, including national insurance and pension contributions, of a prison officer as at 31 March each year since 2010 is contained in the table below.</p><p> </p><p><strong>Mean Annual Pay Cost of Prison Officers, Including Employer National Insurance and Pension Contributions – as at 31 March, 2010 to 2014</strong></p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Year</strong></p><p><strong>- At 31st March </strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Mean Annual Pay Cost (Nominal)</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2010</p></td><td><p>32,747</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011</p></td><td><p>34,024</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012</p></td><td><p>34,951</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013</p></td><td><p>35,608</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014</p></td><td><p>36,157</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>The pay costs shown are for Band 3 Prison Officers and their equivalents and include basic salary and local pay allowance where applicable.</p>","Kenilworth and Southam","Jeremy Wright",,"2014-06-25T09:13:18.962462Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62366/answer","Biography information for Jeremy Wright","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62366/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62366/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2014-06-17","Prison Officers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what the per capita spending on prison officers was in England and Wales in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Dominic Raab","Esher and Walton","Mr Dominic Raab","201042"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62367","Ministry of Justice","false","2014-06-30","<p>The number of offenders found guilty at all courts of the listed offences related to the Licensing Act 2003, in England and Wales, from 2009 to 2013, alongside the number of offenders given the maximum allowable sentence, can be viewed in the table.</p>","Kenilworth and Southam","Jeremy Wright",,"2014-06-30T16:55:57.8239359Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62367/answer","Biography information for Jeremy Wright","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62367/answer","Offenders found guilty at all courts for offences relating to the Licensing Act 2003, England and Wales, 2009-2013.xls","Offenders - Licensing Act 2003 - England and Wales","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62367/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2014-06-17","Licensing Laws","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many people were convicted of an offence under Sections 141, 142, 146, 147A and 149 (1, 3 and 4), 151, 152 or 153 of the Licensing Act 2003 in the last 12 months; and how many of those convicted were fined the maximum amount stipulated in that Act for those offences.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","201058"
