"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62129","Ministry of Justice","false","2014-06-26","<p>As this Government has made previously clear, we will not take any steps to dispose of the mothballed HM Prison Wellingborough because it is sensible measure to retain reserve capacity. I have no immediate plans to change that status.</p><p> </p><p>My office will be in touch to arrange a meeting to further discuss this matter further.</p>","Kenilworth and Southam","Jeremy Wright","200826 ; 200827","2014-06-26T11:03:33.0056315Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62129/answer","Biography information for Jeremy Wright","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62129/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62129/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2014-06-16","Wellingborough Prison","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, if he will meet the hon. Member for Wellingborough to discuss HMP Wellingborough.","false","Biography information for Mr Peter Bone","Wellingborough","Mr Peter Bone","200825"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62130","Ministry of Justice","false","2014-06-26","<p>As this Government has made previously clear, we will not take any steps to dispose of the mothballed HM Prison Wellingborough because it is sensible measure to retain reserve capacity. I have no immediate plans to change that status.</p><p> </p><p>My office will be in touch to arrange a meeting to further discuss this matter further.</p>","Kenilworth and Southam","Jeremy Wright","200825 ; 200827","2014-06-26T11:03:33.0965389Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62130/answer","Biography information for Jeremy Wright","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62130/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62130/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2014-06-16","Wellingborough Prison","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, if he will re-open HMP Wellingborough to increase prison capacity.","false","Biography information for Mr Peter Bone","Wellingborough","Mr Peter Bone","200826"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62131","Ministry of Justice","false","2014-07-08","<p>The Employment tribunal remissions data currently available does not permit this information to be readily obtained and assured.</p>","North West Cambridgeshire","Mr Shailesh Vara",,"2014-07-08T09:21:21.4570922Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62131/answer","Biography information for Mr Shailesh Vara","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62131/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62131/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2014-06-16","Employment Tribunals Service","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many applications for employment tribunal fee remission were (a) received, (b) granted and (c) refused between 1 January and 31 March 2014; and how many such refusals were successfully appealed.","false","Biography information for Andy Slaughter","Hammersmith","Mr Andy Slaughter","200818"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62132","Ministry of Justice","false","2014-06-19","<p /> <p /> <p>The number of mobile phone and SIM card seizures for the first six months of 2013 was 3398. The data for the whole of 2013 will be available by the end of August 2014, broken down by prison establishment.</p><p> </p><p>One seizure may constitute a handset containing one SIM card or media card, a handset only, or a SIM card only.</p><p> </p><p>All figures provided have been drawn from live administrative data systems which may be amended at any time. Although care is taken when processing and analysing the returns, the detail collected is subject to the inaccuracies inherent in any large scale recording system.</p>","Kenilworth and Southam","Jeremy Wright",,"2014-06-19T15:44:36.173727Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62132/answer","Biography information for Jeremy Wright","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62132/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62132/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2014-06-16","Prisons: Mobile Phones","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, with reference to the Answer of 13 May 2014, Official Report, column 494W, on prisons: mobile telephones, when data on mobile telephones seized in prisons in 2013 will be made available.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","200962"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62133","Ministry of Justice","false","2014-06-19","<p /> <p /> <p>We do not centrally hold data on the number of prisoners transferred from closed to open prisons for the time period requested – or the type of sentence which they were serving. Consequently, the information requested could be obtained only at disproportionate cost, as it would involve a manual trawl through the records of every prisoner who has formed part of the prison population since 2010, to identify if they had/have ever been held in open conditions during the time period requested.</p><p> </p><p>Determinate sentence prisoners should not generally be moved to open prison if they have more than 2 years to serve to their earliest release date, unless assessment of a prisoner's individual risks and needs support earlier categorisation to open conditions. Such cases must have the reasons for their categorisation fully documented and confirmed in writing by the Governing Governor.</p><p> </p><p>Indeterminate sentence prisoners do not have fixed release dates, so even if the data on transfers was readily available, it would not be possible to identify a length of time left to be served in these cases.</p><p> </p><p>Depending on the length of tariff and the risk they pose, indeterminate sentenced prisoners (ISPs – both those serving life and IPP sentences) move through their sentence via a series of progressive transfers into lower security establishments in the closed estate and then usually into open conditions. ISPs may be considered for transfer to open conditions up to 3 years before the expiry of their minimum tariff. The decision to transfer ISPs to open conditions is a categorisation decision which is a matter for the Secretary of State. The Secretary of State may take this decision after seeking advice from the Parole Board - or without seeking advice from the Board, where the prisoners demonstrate exceptional progress.</p><p> </p><p>Placing a prisoner in open conditions serves two main purposes. Firstly, it facilitates the eventual resettlement of prisoners into the community, in conditions more similar to those that they will face in the community than closed conditions can provide. Secondly, it allows for risk to be assessed in order to inform release decisions and, should the prisoner secure release, to inform risk management plans for ongoing supervision in the community. Thus, for many prisoners who have spent a considerable amount of time in custody, this can assist in their successful reintegration in the community and help protect the public. To release these prisoners directly from a closed prison without the resettlement benefits of the open estate could lead to higher levels of post-release re-offending.</p><p> </p><p>Keeping the public safe is our priority. That is why this Government has taken action on both releases on temporary licence (ROTL) and absconds from prison. We commissioned a fundamental review of ROTL policy and practice last year and, in March, announced a package of measures to ensure that the public was properly protected. We have brought forward some of those measures so that they begin to take effect immediately; particularly with more serious offenders, where the review concluded that an enhanced risk assessment approach should be taken.</p><p> </p><p>The public have understandable concerns about the failure of some prisoners to return from temporary release from open prison. Keeping the public safe is our priority and we will not allow the actions of a small minority of offenders to undermine public confidence in the prison system. The number of temporary release failures remains very low; less that one failure in every 1,000 releases and about five in every 100,000 releases involving alleged offending, but we take each and every incident seriously. The Government has already ordered immediate changes to tighten up the system as a matter of urgency. With immediate effect, prisoners will no longer be transferred to open conditions if they have previously absconded from open prisons; or if they have failed to return or reoffended whilst released on temporary licence.</p><p> </p>","Kenilworth and Southam","Jeremy Wright",,"2014-06-19T14:08:36.5109478Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62133/answer","Biography information for Jeremy Wright","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62133/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62133/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2014-06-16","Prisoners","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what average time was left to be served on a sentence for prisoners serving (a) determinate, (b) indeterminate, (c) life and (d) all sentences moved from closed to open conditions within the prison estate in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","200961"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62134","Ministry of Justice","false","2014-06-19","<p /> <p /> <p>Keeping the public safe is our priority. Absconds and escapes have reached record lows under this Government but each incident is taken seriously. Immediate changes have already been ordered to tighten up the system as a matter of urgency. Prisoners will no longer be transferred to open conditions or allowed out on temporary release if they have previously absconded, escaped, or attempted to do either.</p><p> </p><p>My officials are currently working to provide the information requested. I will write to you in due course.</p>","Kenilworth and Southam","Jeremy Wright",,"2014-06-19T15:37:24.4508706Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62134/answer","Biography information for Jeremy Wright","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62134/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62134/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2014-06-16","Prisoner Escapes","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many prisoners serving sentences in open conditions have previously absconded for their current or previous establishments (a) once, (b) twice, (c) three times and (d) four or more times.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","200960"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62135","Ministry of Justice","false","2014-06-24","<p /> <p /> <p>We have recently received representations from insolvency practitioners, including the Association of Business Recovery Professionals (R3), regarding a permanent exemption for insolvency litigation from the scope of the costs and funding provisions in Part 2 of the Legal Aid, Sentencing and Punishment of Offenders (LASPO) Act 2012. Ministry of Justice officials have met with R3 on this matter.</p><p> </p><p>The LASPO reforms were implemented generally from 1 April 2013, although they were delayed for insolvency proceedings in order to allow stakeholders time to adjust. The Government's position remains - as announced by written ministerial statement in May 2012 (24 May 2012: Col 94WS) - that the reforms should apply to insolvency proceedings from April 2015.</p>","North West Cambridgeshire","Mr Shailesh Vara",,"2014-06-24T11:52:32.8455347Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62135/answer","Biography information for Mr Shailesh Vara","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62135/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62135/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2014-06-16","Insolvency","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what representations he has had on including insolvency litigation in the scope of the Legal Aid, Sentencing and Punishment of Offenders Act 2012.","false","Biography information for Richard Fuller","Bedford","Richard Fuller","200893"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62136","Ministry of Justice","false","2014-06-19","<p /> <p /> <p>This information is not available centrally and could only be obtained at disproportionate cost.</p><p> </p><p>We want more prisoners to undertake work in prisons, within the discipline of regular working hours, which will also help them develop the skills they need to gain employment, reform, and turn away from crime. To truly expand real work in prison, we need to maximise the involvement of businesses and the rest of Government, making it profitable for companies and to deliver value to the taxpayer.</p><p> </p><p>The number of prisoners working in industrial activity across public sector prisons increased from around 8,600 in 2010-11 (the first year for which figures are available) to around 9,700 in 2012-13. This delivered an increase in the total hours worked in industrial activities from 10.6 million hours to 13.1 million hours. Private sector prisons have also been supporting this agenda and have reported that they delivered over 1½ million prisoner working hours in commercial and industrial workshops in 2012-13 which provided work for over 1,200 prisoners.</p><p> </p><p>In addition there are substantial numbers of prisoners who work to keep prisons running on tasks such as cooking, serving meals, maintenance and cleaning.</p><p> </p><p>Figures for public sector prisons are published in the NOMS Annual Report Management Information Addendum: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/225225/mi-addendum.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/225225/mi-addendum.pdf</a></p><p> </p><p>Figures have been drawn from administrative IT systems, which, as with any large scale recording system, are subject to possible errors with data entry and processing.</p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Kenilworth and Southam","Jeremy Wright",,"2014-06-19T14:04:39.0038857Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62136/answer","Biography information for Jeremy Wright","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62136/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62136/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2014-06-16","Prisons: Employment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what proportion of prisoners in each prison in England and Wales are willing and able to work but cannot do so as a result of a lack of available vacancies in their prison establishment.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","200797"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62137","Attorney General","false","2014-06-19","<p>Increasing the number of rape convictions continues to be a priority in the criminal justice system. On 6 June 2014, a Rape Action Plan was jointly published by the police and Crown Prosecution Service (CPS), which sets out a series of actions designed to improve the criminal justice response in rape cases. This followed a Rape National Scrutiny Panel led by the Director of Public Prosecutions and the National Policing lead for rape, which considered the investigation and prosecution of rape cases including their referral from the police to the CPS. The Action plan can be found on the CPS website at; <a href="http://www.cps.gov.uk/publications/equality/vaw/rape_action_plan.pdf" target="_blank">http://www.cps.gov.uk/publications/equality/vaw/rape_action_plan.pdf</a></p><p> </p>","North East Hertfordshire","Oliver Heald",,"2014-06-19T15:39:55.1205851Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62137/answer","Biography information for Sir Oliver Heald","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62137/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62137/answer",,,,,"88","Attorney General","Attorney General","2014-06-16","Rape","1","House of Commons","To ask the Attorney General, what recent steps his Department has taken to increase the number of rape convictions.","false","Biography information for Dan Jarvis","Barnsley Central","Dan Jarvis","200919"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62138","Northern Ireland Office","false","2014-06-19","<p> </p><p>The hon Member will appreciate that this is a devolved matter. However I take every opportunity to promote the Northern Ireland film industry which has been significantly boosted by the high end television tax credit introduced by my Rt hon Friend the Chancellor of the Exchequer.</p><p>I have met the senior team at Home Box Office on two occasions. Last month I wrote to the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills to coincide with the publication of the UK Creative Industries International Strategy in China, in order to promote some 250 media production companies based in Northern Ireland that are already delivering on a global stage and offering world-class talent across the sector.</p><p> </p>","Chipping Barnet","Mrs Theresa Villiers",,"2014-06-19T13:02:19.6572799Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62138/answer","Biography information for Theresa Villiers","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62138/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62138/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2014-06-16","Film","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, what steps her Department has taken to ensure further opportunities for Northern Ireland's film industry are secured.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","200952"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62139","Northern Ireland Office","false","2014-06-18","<p> </p><p>This is a devolved matter but I took the opportunity of raising it with the Northern Ireland Minister for Employment and Learning, on the hon Member's behalf, when I met him on 18 June.</p><p> </p>","Chipping Barnet","Mrs Theresa Villiers",,"2014-06-18T14:44:33.9799427Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62139/answer","Biography information for Theresa Villiers","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62139/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62139/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2014-06-16","Film and Television","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, what steps her Department is taking to ensure that local colleges train the people of Northern Ireland with the appropriate skills to enable further growth in film and television production in Northern Ireland.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","200950"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62140","Northern Ireland Office","false","2014-06-18","<p> </p><p>Northern Ireland is one of the most beautiful parts of the United Kingdom and the televising around the world of the G8 summit in Fermanagh last year and the recent Giro d'Italia Grande Partenza will doubtless result in new tourist visits.</p><p>The promotion of tourism is a devolved matter, however I take every opportunity to invite those whom I meet to come and visit and enjoy Northern Ireland for themselves.</p><p> </p>","Chipping Barnet","Mrs Theresa Villiers",,"2014-06-18T14:42:00.3236096Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62140/answer","Biography information for Theresa Villiers","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62140/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62140/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2014-06-16","Areas of Outstanding Natural Beauty","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, what steps her Department is taking to promote Northern Ireland's natural beauty to boost its tourism.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","200951"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62141","Northern Ireland Office","false","2014-06-23","<p> </p><p>As the hon Member is aware, the assessment of my Department is that to release the names of individuals granted the RPM years ago would not be appropriate, given the time that has passed since the RPM was last used and the potential legal issues this would raise. There are, of course, means by which names of RPM recipients become public, including in the course of legal proceedings, which is a matter for the courts.</p><p> </p>","Chipping Barnet","Mrs Theresa Villiers",,"2014-06-23T12:57:39.3598604Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62141/answer","Biography information for Theresa Villiers","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62141/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62141/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2014-06-16","Terrorism","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, who the beneficiaries in Northern Ireland of the Royal Prerogative of Mercy granted by means of a Warrant under the Royal Sign Manual were in the last 25 years; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Kate Hoey","Vauxhall","Kate Hoey","200854"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62142","Northern Ireland Office","false","2014-06-19","<p> </p><p>As of 1 June 2014, my Department employed 155 permanent members of staff made up of Home Civil Servants and Northern Ireland Civil Servants staff seconded to the Northern Ireland Office. Three part-time members of staff are engaged on an annual contract.</p><p> </p>","Chipping Barnet","Mrs Theresa Villiers",,"2014-06-19T12:58:37.2344995Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62142/answer","Biography information for Theresa Villiers","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62142/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62142/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2014-06-16","Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, how many (a) permanent and (b) non-permanent staff were employed in her Department on 1 June 2014.","false","Biography information for Mr Ivan Lewis","Bury South","Mr Ivan Lewis","200836"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62143","Northern Ireland Office","false","2014-06-19","<p> </p><p>As the hon Member will know, my Rt hon Friend the Prime Minister opened the International Festival for Business recently. The events will be a great opportunity to showcase the very best of Britain and encourage foreign investors to set up or expand in the UK, including Northern Ireland.</p><p>While I have no plans to visit at present, I fully intend to discuss the Festival when I meet Dominic Jermey, the incoming CEO of UKTI, shortly and the Northern Ireland Minister for Enterprise, Trade and Investment to see how Northern Ireland businesses can best take advantage of the opportunities that it offers.</p><p> </p>","Chipping Barnet","Mrs Theresa Villiers",,"2014-06-19T12:55:58.4470531Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62143/answer","Biography information for Theresa Villiers","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62143/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62143/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2014-06-16","Business","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, whether she plans to attend the International Festival for Business in Liverpool.","false","Biography information for Mr Ivan Lewis","Bury South","Mr Ivan Lewis","200837"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62144","Northern Ireland Office","false","2014-06-19","<p> </p><p>I met Nelson McCausland MLA in Stormont House to discuss a range of matters. The meeting lasted 45 minutes.</p><p> </p>","Chipping Barnet","Mrs Theresa Villiers",,"2014-06-19T13:08:52.4066589Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62144/answer","Biography information for Theresa Villiers","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62144/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62144/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2014-06-16","Northern Ireland Executive Department for Social Development","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, where and for what purpose she held her meeting with the Northern Ireland Minister for Social Development on 8 May 2014; and what the duration was of that meeting.","false","Biography information for Mr Ivan Lewis","Bury South","Mr Ivan Lewis","200835"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62145","Northern Ireland Office","false","2014-06-19","<p> </p><p>I discussed a range of topics with Nelson McCausland MLA at our meeting on 8 May 2014.</p><p> </p>","Chipping Barnet","Mrs Theresa Villiers",,"2014-06-19T13:07:05.437429Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62145/answer","Biography information for Theresa Villiers","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62145/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62145/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2014-06-16","Northern Ireland Executive Department for Social Development","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, what topics were discussed at her meeting with the Northern Ireland Minister for Social Development on 8 May 2014.","false","Biography information for Mr Ivan Lewis","Bury South","Mr Ivan Lewis","200834"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62146","Northern Ireland Office","false","2014-06-19","<p> </p><p>It has not been possible to meet the outgoing Chief Executive of UKTI. I look forward to meeting Dominic Jermey in the coming weeks to discuss how UKTI can promote Northern Ireland trade and investment working in tandem with InvestNI.</p><p> </p>","Chipping Barnet","Mrs Theresa Villiers",,"2014-06-19T13:05:38.5109508Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62146/answer","Biography information for Theresa Villiers","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62146/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62146/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2014-06-16","Foreign Investment in UK","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, when she last met the Chief Executive of UK Trade & Investment to discuss that organisation's role in attracting inward investment to Northern Ireland.","false","Biography information for Mr Ivan Lewis","Bury South","Mr Ivan Lewis","200804"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62147","Northern Ireland Office","false","2014-06-23","<p> </p><p>The Northern Ireland Office sits on the Department for Culture, Media and Sport Programme Board for First World War Centenary Commemorations and plays a coordination role in ensuring the Government's programme for the First World War commemorations is implemented in Northern Ireland in a manner that promotes reconciliation and enhances prospects for a peaceful, shared future. This includes plans to implement the Government's commemorative paving stones project in the hometowns of Victoria Cross recipients.</p><p>I am working closely with the Irish Government to participate in a series of joint commemoration events for the centenary of the First World War, and the wider decade of centenaries.</p><p>My officials also provide support for local centenary commemoration plans by sitting on, and working closely with, the Northern Ireland First World War Centenary Committee chaired by the Rt hon Jeffrey Donaldson MP. I receive regular updates on this work and lend it my full support.</p><p> </p>","Chipping Barnet","Mrs Theresa Villiers",,"2014-06-23T13:00:47.2765721Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62147/answer","Biography information for Theresa Villiers","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62147/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62147/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2014-06-16","World War I","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, what steps she is taking to support the progress of the First World War legacy project in Northern Ireland; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Lady Hermon","North Down","Lady Hermon","200782"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62148","Northern Ireland Office","false","2014-06-23","<p> </p><p>I have regular discussions with ministerial colleagues, including in the Foreign and Commonwealth Office, on the importance of promoting Northern Ireland trade and investment.</p><p>Our Embassies abroad regularly work with InvestNI and the Northern Ireland Executive to assist with trade missions led by Northern Ireland Ministers. I shall be discussing with the incoming UKTI Chief Executive shortly how best UKTI posts abroad can work even closer with their counterparts in InvestNI.</p><p> </p>","Chipping Barnet","Mrs Theresa Villiers",,"2014-06-23T13:02:46.5203774Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62148/answer","Biography information for Theresa Villiers","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62148/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62148/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2014-06-16","Overseas Trade","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, what discussions she has had with her ministerial colleagues at the Foreign and Commonwealth Office on how the UK's overseas posts may be used more effectively to promote Northern Ireland trade and investment.","false","Biography information for Mr Ivan Lewis","Bury South","Mr Ivan Lewis","200760"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62149","Department for Culture Media and Sport","false","2014-06-23","<p>The previous Secretary of State, the Rt. Hon Maria Miller MP announced in October last year a commitment of £10million of funding from the Heritage Lottery Fund for projects marking some of the UK's most important anniversaries and commemorative events including Agincourt 600. This will ensure that those moments which form a central part of our national history are commemorated and understood by people today.</p>","Maidstone and The Weald","Mrs Helen Grant",,"2014-06-23T12:59:33.2738677Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62149/answer","Biography information for Mrs Helen Grant","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62149/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62149/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2014-06-16","Hundred Years’ War: Anniversaries","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what plans he has put in place to commemorate the 600th anniversary of the Battles of Harfleur and Agincourt.","false","Biography information for Jim Dowd","Lewisham West and Penge","Jim Dowd","200865"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62150","Scotland Office","false","2014-06-23","<p>The Government does not collate figures for the level of investment in Scotland that results from UK membership of the EU.</p>","Dumfriesshire, Clydesdale and Tweeddale","David Mundell",,"2014-06-23T16:26:58.5173804Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62150/answer","Biography information for David Mundell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62150/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62150/answer",,,,,"2","Scotland","Scotland","2014-06-16","UK Membership of EU","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Scotland, what recent estimate he has made of the level of investment in (a) Glasgow North West constituency, (b) Glasgow and (c) Scotland that resulted from EU membership in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for John Robertson","Glasgow North West","John Robertson","200767"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62151","Scotland Office","false","2014-06-23","<p>The Government does not collate figures for the number of jobs in Scotland that depend on UK membership of the EU. However, independent analysis published by the Centre for Economics and Business Research in March 2014 suggested that, in 2011, approximately 335,000 jobs in Scotland were associated with Scottish exports to the EU. The analysis was not broken down to the level of individual UK cities or by Parliamentary constituency</p>","Dumfriesshire, Clydesdale and Tweeddale","David Mundell",,"2014-06-23T16:24:36.8599544Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62151/answer","Biography information for David Mundell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62151/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62151/answer",,,,,"2","Scotland","Scotland","2014-06-16","UK Membership of EU","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Scotland, what recent assessment he has made of the effects of membership of the EU on jobs in (a) Glasgow North West constituency, (b) Glasgow and (c) Scotland.","false","Biography information for John Robertson","Glasgow North West","John Robertson","200756"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62152","Deputy Prime Minister","false","2014-06-19","<p>The total cost to-date of What Staying in the United Kingdom Means for Scotland is £723,501 (plus VAT).</p><p>Each booklet cost around 30p to design, produce, print and deliver to every household in Scotland. As is standard practice, detail and spending data will published in the Cabinet Office transparency returns.</p><p> </p>","Tunbridge Wells","Greg Clark","200948","2014-06-19T16:19:42.2074899Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62152/answer","Biography information for Greg Clark","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62152/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62152/answer",,,,,"58","Deputy Prime Minister","Deputy Prime Minister","2014-06-16","Sovereignty","1","House of Commons","To ask the Deputy Prime Minister, what the total cost was of production and delivery of the booklet, What staying in the United Kingdom means for Scotland; and what proportion of such costs relate to (a) research, verification and co-ordination, (b) writing, editing, sub-editing and proofing of the text, (c) photography, design, artwork and licensing, (d) printing, (e) distribution and delivery and (f) related communications, administration and public affairs support.","false","Biography information for Mike Weir","Angus","Mr Mike Weir","200946"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62153","Scotland Office","false","2014-06-25","<p> </p><p>The total UK Government cost to-date of ‘What Staying in the United Kingdom Means for Scotland' is £723,501 (plus VAT).</p><p>This works out at the equivalent of 30p per household for the entire process of design, production and delivery. Further detail will be published in the usual fashion in the Cabinet Office transparency returns.</p><p>The Scotland Office incurred no costs in the production or creation of the booklet. Staffing costs were taken from existing Scotland Office budgets.</p><p> </p>","Dumfriesshire, Clydesdale and Tweeddale","David Mundell",,"2014-06-25T14:03:19.5219448Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62153/answer","Biography information for David Mundell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62153/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62153/answer",,,,,"2","Scotland","Scotland","2014-06-16","Sovereignty","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Scotland, what estimate he has made of the total costs incurred (a) in his Department and (b) in the Government of the creation and production of the booklet, What staying in the United Kingdom means for Scotland.","false","Biography information for Mike Weir","Angus","Mr Mike Weir","200947"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62154","Deputy Prime Minister","false","2014-06-19","<p>The total cost to-date of What Staying in the United Kingdom Means for Scotland is £723,501 (plus VAT).</p><p>Each booklet cost around 30p to design, produce, print and deliver to every household in Scotland. As is standard practice, detail and spending data will published in the Cabinet Office transparency returns.</p><p> </p>","Tunbridge Wells","Greg Clark","200946","2014-06-19T16:19:42.2856199Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62154/answer","Biography information for Greg Clark","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62154/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62154/answer",,,,,"58","Deputy Prime Minister","Deputy Prime Minister","2014-06-16","Sovereignty","1","House of Commons","To ask the Deputy Prime Minister, what estimate he has made of the charges made by external (a) public affairs consultants, (b) creative agencies and (c) printing, logistics and delivery companies for work relating to the production of the booklet, What staying in the United Kingdom means for Scotland.","false","Biography information for Mike Weir","Angus","Mr Mike Weir","200948"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62155","Department for Transport","false","2014-06-23","<p> </p><p>In order to test the case for HS2, current fares were assumed to increase by RPI+1% annually until 2036 after which fares are assumed to grow in line with inflation. No fares differential was applied to services using the high speed infrastructure. This is an assumption which provides an appropriate basis for modelling costs and benefits, but does not represent a prediction of future rail fares, which will be affected by government policy, market and industry changes across the GB rail network over many years.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2014-06-23T13:55:15.5705956Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62155/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62155/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62155/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2014-06-16","High Speed 2 Railway Line","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what recent estimate he has made of projected ticket prices for rail passengers using the High Speed 2 rail line.","false","Biography information for Mr Barry Sheerman","Huddersfield","Mr Barry Sheerman","200848"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62156","Department for Transport","false","2014-06-23","<p>As was the case under previous administrations, details of internal meetings are not normally disclosed.</p>","Wimbledon","Stephen Hammond",,"2014-06-23T13:53:01.4688304Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62156/answer","Biography information for Stephen Hammond","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62156/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62156/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2014-06-16","Chief Scientific Advisers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how many meetings he has had with his Department's Chief Scientific Adviser in the last 12 months.","false","Biography information for Liam Byrne","Birmingham, Hodge Hill","Mr Liam Byrne","200793"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62157","Department for Transport","false","2014-06-23","<p> </p><p>There are currently no plans to publish information relating to the likely structure or level of ticket prices for journeys using the HS2 railway following the opening of HS2 Phase One in 2026 and beyond.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2014-06-23T13:57:30.6719357Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62157/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62157/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62157/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2014-06-16","High Speed 2 Railway Line","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, when he expects to publish information on ticket pricing for High Speed 2.","false","Biography information for Mr Barry Sheerman","Huddersfield","Mr Barry Sheerman","200851"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62158","Department for Transport","false","2014-06-23","<p> </p><p>The HS2 business case demonstrates that the project can deliver significant benefits for the country without any fares differential being required for journeys using the high speed line. It is too soon to know what fares will be set for travel on HS2 services. Government decisions about fares structures and regulation will be taken closer to the commencement of HS2 Phase One services in 2026.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2014-06-23T13:56:29.3028054Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62158/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62158/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62158/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2014-06-16","High Speed 2 Railway Line","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, whether he expects High Speed 2 will require a separate ticket pricing structure from regular rail services.","false","Biography information for Mr Barry Sheerman","Huddersfield","Mr Barry Sheerman","200850"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62159","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2014-06-19","<p /> <p /> <p>The information you have requested is not currently available.<strong>     </strong></p><p> </p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2014-06-19T11:48:20.6361086Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62159/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62159/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62159/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2014-06-16","Personal Independence Payment: Warrington","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many people in (a) Warrington and (b) Warrington North constituency who have submitted a claim for personal independence payment have been waiting more than (a) six months and (b) three months for a medical assessment.","false","Biography information for Helen Jones","Warrington North","Helen Jones","200828"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62160","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2014-06-24","<p /> <p /> <p>For those granted leave to remain as a result of a successful asylum claim, a joint fast track National Insurance number application process operates between DWP and the Home Office.</p>","Wirral West","Esther McVey",,"2014-06-24T16:41:09.4643885Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62160/answer","Biography information for Esther McVey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62160/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62160/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2014-06-16","National Insurance: Asylum","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what steps he is taking to ensure that asylum seekers are able to receive a National Insurance number without unnecessary delay.","false","Biography information for Andy McDonald","Middlesbrough","Andy McDonald","200843"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62161","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2014-06-23","<p /> <p /> <p>There have been no changes in the number of interpreters available at Middlesbrough Jobcentre (James Cook House, 79 Corporation Road, Middlesbrough, TS1 2BA) in the last 12 months.</p>","Wirral West","Esther McVey",,"2014-06-23T15:05:48.0295351Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62161/answer","Biography information for Esther McVey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62161/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62161/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2014-06-16","Jobcentres: Middlesbrough","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what estimate he has made of changes in the number of interpreters available at Middlesbrough Jobcentre in the last 12 months.","false","Biography information for Andy McDonald","Middlesbrough","Andy McDonald","200844"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62162","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2014-06-19","<p /> <p /> <p>As was the case under previous administrations, details of internal meetings are not normally disclosed.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Wirral West","Esther McVey",,"2014-06-19T15:34:39.059718Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62162/answer","Biography information for Esther McVey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62162/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62162/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2014-06-16","Chief Scientific Advisers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many meetings he has had with his Department's Chief Scientific Adviser in the last 12 months.","false","Biography information for Liam Byrne","Birmingham, Hodge Hill","Mr Liam Byrne","200795"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62163","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2014-06-24","<p /> <p /> <p>Asylum seekers are normally excluded from claiming most benefits.</p><p>Those who cannot claim benefits receive support provided by Asylum Support, a part of the Home Office that deals with accommodating and supporting asylum seekers and their dependants.</p>","Wirral West","Esther McVey",,"2014-06-24T16:33:45.3050946Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62163/answer","Biography information for Esther McVey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62163/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62163/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2014-06-16","Social Security Benefits: Asylum","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what steps he has taken to ensure that asylum seekers receive the benefits to which they are entitled.","false","Biography information for Andy McDonald","Middlesbrough","Andy McDonald","200845"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62164","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2014-06-26","<p> </p><p> </p><p>Measures taken ensure that dedicated centralised teams are able to offer both earlier and increased numbers of appointments to individuals of the North East. Measures are also in place to ensure mobile visits to employer sites are completed when necessary.</p>","Wirral West","Esther McVey",,"2014-06-26T15:06:59.513667Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62164/answer","Biography information for Esther McVey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62164/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62164/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2014-06-16","National Insurance Contributions Office: Newcastle Upon Tyne","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what steps he has taken to ensure that the centralisation in Newcastle of national insurance services for the North East does not have a negative effect on service for users.","false","Biography information for Andy McDonald","Middlesbrough","Andy McDonald","200846"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62165","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2014-06-25","<p /> <p /> <p>Newcastle was chosen as the National Insurance centre for residents of Middlesbrough as it has centralised expertise in administering applications for National Insurance numbers. Given this expertise, proximity to Middlesbrough and availability of public transport, Newcastle provides a viable service that maintains the level of expertise and security required</p>","Wirral West","Esther McVey",,"2014-06-25T14:38:29.7247474Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62165/answer","Biography information for Esther McVey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62165/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62165/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2014-06-16","National Insurance Contributions Office: Newcastle Upon Tyne","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, for what reason Newcastle was chosen as the National Insurance centre for residents of Middlesbrough; and what effect this choice is having on service provision.","false","Biography information for Andy McDonald","Middlesbrough","Andy McDonald","200847"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62166","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2014-06-23","<p /> <p /> <p>The Secretary of State has not had recent discussions with Glasgow City Council on the Glasgow Guarantee.</p>","Wirral West","Esther McVey",,"2014-06-23T14:59:36.1477969Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62166/answer","Biography information for Esther McVey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62166/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62166/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2014-06-16","Employment Schemes: Glasgow","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what recent discussions he has had with Glasgow City Council on the Glasgow Guarantee.","false","Biography information for John Robertson","Glasgow North West","John Robertson","200754"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62167","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2014-06-23","<p /> <p /> <p>Information on the number of National Insurance Numbers registered to individuals including new workers, via constituency, county and country, can be found at:</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p><p><a href="https://stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/" target="_blank">https://stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk</a></p><p> </p><p>Guidance on how to extract the information required can be found at:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://sw.stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/webapi/online-help/Stat-Xplore_User_Guide.htm" target="_blank">https://sw.stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/webapi/online-help/Stat-Xplore_User_Guide.htm</a></p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Wirral West","Esther McVey",,"2014-06-23T17:00:02.6258255Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62167/answer","Biography information for Esther McVey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62167/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62167/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2014-06-16","National Insurance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what recent estimate he has made of the number of (a) new national insurance numbers registered and (b) new workers in (i) Bury St Edmunds constituency, (ii) Suffolk and (iii) England and Wales in the latest period for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Mr David Ruffley","Bury St Edmunds","Mr David Ruffley","200746"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62168","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2014-06-19","<p /> <p /> <p>Since the Child Maintenance Service launched in December 2012 we have been talking to clients (via caseworkers and through our Child Maintenance Options service) about the planned introduction of charging, and letters to Child Maintenance Service clients have made reference to the charges.</p><p> </p><p>More widely we have engaged with stakeholders, partners, MP caseworkers and intermediaries to share information about the reforms to the child maintenance system.</p><p> </p><p>Ahead of existing Child Support Agency cases closing, a regional media trial is currently running in the Manchester area. The media activity includes digital, radio and press advertising to let parents know that the Child Support Agency is changing and to reassure them that they don't need to take any action until they receive a letter. We will evaluate the results of this media activity before confirming plans to run this campaign nationally later this year.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Thornbury and Yate","Steve Webb",,"2014-06-19T12:11:57.9124796Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62168/answer","Biography information for Steve Webb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62168/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62168/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2014-06-16","Children: Maintenance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what steps he is taking to publicise information on changes to child maintenance.","false","Biography information for John Robertson","Glasgow North West","John Robertson","200763"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62169","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2014-06-23","<p /> <p /> <p>The department has not made an estimate regarding the additional costs for claimants living in rural communities. Providing such an estimate would require the DWP to differentiate the costs to rural claimants from those elsewhere. This can only be done at disproportionate cost to the department. However, the department does have some flexibility to meet the needs of those living in rural areas: for example, postal signing can be offered and claimants attending interviews on days outside their normal day of attendance can have their travelling expenses reimbursed. Additionally, Work Coaches are also able to use the Flexible Support Fund and issue Travel Discount Cards to help claimants with travel expenses.</p>","Wirral West","Esther McVey",,"2014-06-23T17:04:52.5473816Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62169/answer","Biography information for Esther McVey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62169/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62169/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2014-06-16","Jobcentres","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what estimate he has made of the additional costs to claimants living in rural communities of travel to attend jobcentre interviews for (a) fortnightly signing and (b) other interviews and advisory meetings.","false","Biography information for Cathy Jamieson","Kilmarnock and Loudoun","Cathy Jamieson","200780"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62170","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2014-06-19","<p /> <p /> <p>The latest information that we hold on Youth Contract Wage Incentives was published in February 2014 and can be found at the link below:</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/283873/youth-contract-feb14.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/283873/youth-contract-feb14.pdf</a></p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>Wage incentives are a demand-led scheme, and we have not forecast the number of wage incentives we expect to be taken up by April 2015.</p>","Wirral West","Esther McVey",,"2014-06-19T14:11:52.1995498Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62170/answer","Biography information for Esther McVey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62170/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62170/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2014-06-16","Employment Schemes: Young People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many youth contract wage incentives he estimates will be taken up by April 2015.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","200921"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62171","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2014-06-19","<p /> <p /> <p>The Work Programme is continuing to offer tailored support to those people over 50 at risk of becoming long-term unemployed and providers are continuing to design support based on their individual need.</p><p>Last year, the Government launched the Work Programme ‘Building Best Practice Group', which is considering the best ways of addressing the particular needs of claimants, including older workers. The group will report back to Ministers later in 2014.</p>","Wirral West","Esther McVey",,"2014-06-19T11:57:10.1558032Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62171/answer","Biography information for Esther McVey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62171/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62171/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2014-06-16","Work Programme: Older Workers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what steps he is taking to improve support for people over 50 provided through the Work Programme.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","200920"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62172","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2014-06-19","<p /> <p /> <p>Headline figures on the number of unfilled vacancies at a point in time are published by the Office for National Statistics, based on a regular survey of employers. The sample size of the survey is, however, too small to allow information to be published below national level.</p><p> </p><p>Jobcentre vacancies are just a part of total recruitment, missing jobs available in the wider labour market beyond the local constituency and those coming up through other recruitment channels or filled by direct approaches to employers or word of mouth. A snapshot of unfilled vacancies also misses the regular turnover of new vacancies that come up as existing opportunities are filled. Information on the number of unfilled Jobcentre Plus vacancies was collected until 2012 and the available information is shown in the table. Consistent information on benefits other than Jobseeker's Allowance (JSA) is not available for parliamentary constituencies over this period.</p><p> </p><p>Jobseeker's Allowance caseload and unfilled Jobcentre Plus vacancies</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td colspan="2"><p>Warrington North</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>November in each year</p></td><td><p>Jobseeker's Allowance claimants</p></td><td><p>Live unfilled vacancies</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2007</p></td><td><p>1,146</p></td><td><p>1,750</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2008</p></td><td><p>1,789</p></td><td><p>692</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2009</p></td><td><p>2,618</p></td><td><p>539</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2010</p></td><td><p>2,244</p></td><td><p>955</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011</p></td><td><p>2,523</p></td><td><p>1,005</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012</p></td><td><p>2,529</p></td><td><p>1,495</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>The latest claimant count figures show the number of JSA claimants in Warrington North has fallen to 1,474 in May 2014. <br></p><p>Universal Jobmatch has replaced the previous Jobcentre Plus system of taking vacancies. Equivalent statistical information on vacancies available through the new service is not currently available. The ONS data shows that nationally there are well over 600,000 vacancies available at any one time. Vacancies available locally through Universal Jobmatch can be accessed at <a href="https://www.gov.uk/jobsearch" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/jobsearch</a> . Inputting a postcode, town or place in the appropriate box returns vacancies within a 20 mile radius. This can be further refined as necessary.<br></p>","Wirral West","Esther McVey",,"2014-06-19T15:03:04.7239233Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62172/answer","Biography information for Esther McVey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62172/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62172/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2014-06-16","Unemployment Benefits: Warrington","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many people for each jobcentre plus vacancy were claiming out-of-work benefits in Warrington North constituency in each year since 2007.","false","Biography information for Helen Jones","Warrington North","Helen Jones","200917"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62173","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2014-06-23","<p /> <p /> <p>The UK state pension is payable worldwide. However, where a recipient is not ordinarily resident in the UK, eligibility for annual up-rates is generally restricted to people living in a country which is a member of the European Economic Area, including by extension Switzerland, or in a country with which the UK has a bilateral social security agreement that provides for up-rating of the UK state pension. A list of these countries can be found at</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/state-pensions-annual-increases-if-you-live-abroad" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/state-pensions-annual-increases-if-you-live-abroad</a></p><p><br> Restricting the availability of annual up-rates to the UK state pensions in this manner has been the long standing policy of successive Governments. This Government has no plans to change it.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p>","Thornbury and Yate","Steve Webb",,"2014-06-23T14:52:32.5766104Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62173/answer","Biography information for Steve Webb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62173/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62173/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2014-06-16","State Retirement Pensions: British Nationals Abroad","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what his policy is on the freezing of state pensions for those living overseas.","false","Biography information for Richard Fuller","Bedford","Richard Fuller","200894"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62268","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2014-06-19","<p>The UK enjoys a stable and secure energy supply, and we are working hard to ensure that it continues. As a Government, we are actively managing a number of risks to our current and future energy supplies, including the current challenges from Iraq, Russia and Ukraine. Our recent national gas risk assessment demonstrated that our gas infrastructure is robust. The measures recently announced by National Grid respond to the energy crunch that, owing to the legacy of under-investment and neglect, was predicted for this winter, but which will not now happen.</p>","Kingston and Surbiton","Mr Edward Davey",,"2014-06-19T14:02:18.9495368Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62268/answer","Biography information for Sir Edward Davey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62268/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62268/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2014-06-16","Energy Supply","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, what assessment he has made of the UK's security of energy supply.","false","Biography information for Glyn Davies","Montgomeryshire","Glyn Davies","904346"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62391","Department for Transport","false","2014-06-19","<p>The Department for Transport and the Highways Agency are already working closely through a Strategic Partners Group, which includes the Department for Business, Innovation and Skills, the Department for Communities and Local Government, the Homes and Community Agency, local authorities, Local Enterprise Partnerships and private sector developers, on the transport infrastructure proposals - including the provision of a new junction 10A on the A14 - in relation to the East Kettering Development site.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Department and the Highways Agency would be happy to work additionally with the Department for Energy and Climate Change and the Cabinet Office on the provision of transport infrastructure in relation to the proposals for an Energy Park and low carbon business at this location.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2014-06-19T12:49:41.6320714Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62391/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62391/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62391/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2014-06-16","A14: Northamptonshire","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, if his Department will work with the Department for Communities and Local Government, the Cabinet Office, the Northamptonshire and South East Midlands LEPs and local authorities to help secure funding for a new junction 10A on the A14 which is required to facilitate the creation of a 60MW renewable energy park and low carbon business park between Burton Latimer and Kettering.","false","Biography information for Mr Philip Hollobone","Kettering","Mr Philip Hollobone","904342"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62633","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2014-06-25","<p>The Coalition Government is committed to fighting fuel poverty through the installation of robust energy efficiency measures.</p><p> </p><p>Statistics published this morning show that from the start of 2013 to the end of April 2014, 394,000 low-income and vulnerable consumers, or households in specified areas of low income, had benefitted from energy efficiency measures being installed under the new Energy Company Obligation.</p>","Bexhill and Battle","Gregory Barker",,"2014-06-25T14:59:05.0155375Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62633/answer","Biography information for Lord Barker of Battle","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62633/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/62633/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2014-06-16","Housing: Insulation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, how many households with a below-average income have received support for comprehensive insulation of their homes in the last year.","false","Biography information for Fiona Mactaggart","Slough","Fiona Mactaggart","904340"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61852","HM Treasury","false","2014-06-23","<p>The Financial Ombudsman Service (FOS) is an independent, non-Governmental body and questions about its funding are a matter for the FOS or, as the case may be, the Financial Conduct Authority (FCA), who approve the FOS budget and fee rules. This question has been passed on to the FOS, and the FOS will reply directly to the honourable member by letter. A copy of the letter will be placed in the Library of the House.</p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2014-06-23T15:49:04.0268588Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61852/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61852/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61852/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2014-06-13","Financial Ombudsman Service","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how much funding of the Financial Ombudsman Service came directly from the levy on the Office of Fair Trading licences on consumer credit firms in (a) 2011, (b) 2012 and (c) 2013; how this funding will be levied in future; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Sir Peter Bottomley","Worthing West","Sir Peter Bottomley","200700"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61853","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2014-06-18","<p> </p><p>My Rt Hon Friend the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills met civil society organisations during his visit and discussed a range of human rights issues, including the rule of law, labour and trade union rights.</p><p> </p>","Sevenoaks","Michael Fallon",,"2014-06-18T16:28:01.8913985Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61853/answer","Biography information for Sir Michael Fallon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61853/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61853/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2014-06-13","China","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what discussions he had on human rights during his recent visit to China.","false","Biography information for Kerry McCarthy","Bristol East","Kerry McCarthy","200693"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61854","HM Treasury","false","2014-06-18","<p><strong>On the 23 May the Government published a further consultation on the delivery of childcare accounts within Tax-Free Childcare. The consultation will be open until 27 June and the Government will consider the responses alongside those to the first consultation before it makes its decision on the provision of childcare accounts.</strong></p>","Loughborough","Nicky Morgan",,"2014-06-18T16:01:13.613892Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61854/answer","Biography information for Nicky Morgan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61854/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61854/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2014-06-13","National Savings and Investments","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, when the decision was taken that National Savings and Investments would be responsible for the delivery of tax-free childcare; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Catherine McKinnell","Newcastle upon Tyne North","Catherine McKinnell","200714"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61855","HM Treasury","false","2014-06-18","<p>National Savings &amp; Investments is an executive agency of the Treasury. As with all of its supporting agencies and public bodies, the Treasury holds regular meetings with NS&amp;I on a wide range of issues.</p>","Loughborough","Nicky Morgan",,"2014-06-18T16:02:17.8260659Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61855/answer","Biography information for Nicky Morgan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61855/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61855/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2014-06-13","National Savings and Investments","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many meetings (a) Ministers and (b) officials in his Department had with representatives of National Savings and Investments in (i) August 2013, (ii) September 2013, (iii) October 2013, (iv) November 2013, (v) December 2013, (vi) January 2014, (vii) February 2014 and (viii) March 2014.","false","Biography information for Catherine McKinnell","Newcastle upon Tyne North","Catherine McKinnell","200703"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61856","HM Treasury","false","2014-06-23","<p>The Financial Conduct Authority (FCA) consumer credit regulatory regime is far better resourced and has wider objectives than the previous Office of Fair Trading (OFT) regime. The FCA is an independent, non-governmental body, and it is entirely funded by the fees it charges on the financial services industry. As a result, specific questions around fees are a matter for the FCA.</p><p> </p><p>The Financial Ombudsman Service (FOS) is funded by a combination of industry levy and case fees. The FOS is an independent, non-Governmental body and questions about its funding are a matter for the FOS or, as the case may be, the FCA (who approve the FOS budget and fee rules). The FOS budget is proposed by FOS annually and approved by the FCA.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Money Advice Service's (MAS) budget is proposed by MAS annually, based on demand for money and debt advice, and approved by the FCA. Consumer credit firms will pay the MAS levy once authorised by the FCA. The FCA has approved MAS's 2014/15 budget, but MAS's budget for future years has not yet been determined.</p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2014-06-23T15:46:33.3002112Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61856/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61856/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61856/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2014-06-13","Money Advice Service and Financial Ombudsman Service","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what estimate he has made of the expected increase in the fees and levies on regulated consumer credit firms that will go towards the funding of the Money Advice Service and Financial Ombudsman Service in (a) 2015, (b) 2016 and (c) 2017 under the new Financial Conduct Authority regulated fees and levies regime.","false","Biography information for Sir Peter Bottomley","Worthing West","Sir Peter Bottomley","200701"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61857","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2014-06-26","<p> </p><p><em>[Holding Reply: Wednesday 18 June 2014]</em></p><p> </p><p> </p><p>According to the English Housing Survey, in 2011-12, there were 3.9 million households in the owner occupied sector with dependent children, 1.3 million in the private rented sector and 1.2 million in the social rented sector.</p><p> </p>","Keighley","Kris Hopkins",,"2014-06-26T16:09:24.6896189Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61857/answer","Biography information for Kris Hopkins","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61857/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61857/answer","Keighley","Kris Hopkins","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61857/answer/previousversion/2363","Biography information for Kris Hopkins","7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2014-06-13","Private Rented Housing: Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what assessment he has made of the number of households with children in the private rented sector in England.","false","Biography information for Hilary Benn","Leeds Central","Hilary Benn","200690"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61858","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2014-06-18","<p> </p><p>At this point in time, this information is not centrally held.</p><p>However, I refer the rt. hon. Member to the Written Ministerial Statement of 16 June 2014, <em>Official Report</em>, Column 71-72WS, on the steps we are taking to promote the use of Local Development Orders on brownfield land.</p><p>In addition, the Written Ministerial Statement of 10 June 2014, <em>Official Report</em>, Column 33WS, provides a broader summary of steps we have taken to facilitate empty and redundant land and property being brought back into productive use.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles",,"2014-06-18T16:12:38.4486695Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61858/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61858/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61858/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2014-06-13","Derelict Land","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what proportion of brownfield land in England is covered by a Local Development Order.","false","Biography information for Hilary Benn","Leeds Central","Hilary Benn","200691"
